  "updatedAt": "2026-04-17T20:51:38.026Z",
  "inventory": "# Codebase Inventory — Spider Dispatch Gating via `spider.follows`\n\n## Scope & blast radius\n\nThree packages change. Two apparatus (Spider, Clerk via kit substrate) and one app page (Oculus writ page).\n\n| Package | Role in this change |\n|---|---|\n| `packages/plugins/spider` | Registers the new kind via `supportKit.linkKinds`; implements gating, stuck cascade, auto-unstick, and cycle detection inside `trySpawn`/the crawl loop. Writes `status.spider` sub-slot via `ClerkApi.setWritStatus`. |\n| `packages/plugins/clerk` | No new code. Consumes the new `linkKinds` contribution via the already-built kit-registry substrate. Its `link()` validator accepts the new kind id automatically; `setWritStatus` is the write path for provenance; `listKinds()` is read by the Oculus form. |\n| `packages/plugins/clerk/pages/writs` | Adds a `kind` dropdown to the inline add-link form. Fetches available kinds from `/api/writ/link-kinds`. Wires inline error surfacing. |\n\nNo changes to `@shardworks/tools-apparatus` (Instrumentarium), Animator, Loom, Stacks, Fabricator, Hopper, or Ratchet. No new guild-level apparatus. No changes to `guild.json`.\n\n### Cross-cutting concerns\n\n- **Per-plugin status slot writer count.** This commission becomes the *first* writer into `WritDoc.status.<pluginId>`. The slot was landed in the status-convention commission but has no live writer today. The pattern used here will be the lived precedent for future plugin consumers (Animator, Hopper, etc.).\n- **Link-kind registry consumer count.** First real consumer of the `kind` field for load-bearing behavior. The registry and validation path are already in Clerk; this commission exercises them end-to-end for the first time.\n- **Two distinct Spider→stuck cascade paths.** Today Spider has one path: `rig.status === 'stuck'` CDC handler (engine cascade; writes resolution only, no status slot). This commission adds a *second* path: pre-dispatch gating (writes `status.spider.stuckCause` plus resolution). Auto-unstick logic must skip writs whose sub-slot is absent, so the engine-cascade path is untouched by design. Worth flagging: two similar-looking transitions with distinct provenance conventions.\n- **Polling semantics.** Gate evaluation is piggy-backed on the existing crawl loop. The same poll that picks new open writs also re-walks blockers for currently-gated and currently-stuck writs. No new scheduler or tick substrate.\n- **Link direction convention.** Source → target means \"source depends on target.\" Spider reads *outbound* links on the candidate, not inbound on the target. Same edge; the outbound read matches the directional semantics of the kind name.\n\n## Key types and interfaces\n\n### Spider (`packages/plugins/spider/src/`)\n\n- `types.ts` — `CrawlResult` discriminated union (`collected` | `grafted` | `dispatched` | `spawned` | `blocked`), `SpiderConfig`, `RigDoc`, `EngineInstance`. Will need a new `CrawlResult` variant for gating outcomes if we want parity with `blocked` (see D4). Also the place where a `SpiderStatusDoc` shape (shape of `status.spider`) belongs if we emit a typed export (see D1).\n- `spider.ts` — main crawl loop. Key sites:\n  - `crawl()` — priority order is **collect > processGrafts > checkBlocked > run > spawn**. `trySpawn` is where we hook gating; `checkBlocked` (different concept — rig-level blocker checks) is unrelated to `spider.follows`. Naming collision worth noting but not resolved here.\n  - `trySpawn()` (~line 1788) — loops open writs of dispatchable types, checks for an existing rig, calls `fabricator.spawnRig`. Insertion point for gating: *after* the \"existing rig\" early-return, *before* rig creation, for each candidate writ.\n  - CDC on rigs book (~line 2172) — when `rig.status === 'stuck'`, transitions writ to `stuck` with `resolution = failedEngine?.error`. Does **not** write `status.spider`. This is the engine-cascade path that auto-unstick must ignore.\n  - `supportKit` declaration (~line 2031) — `requires: ['stacks', 'clerk', 'fabricator']`, `consumes: ['blockTypes', 'rigTemplates', 'rigTemplateMappings']`. Add `linkKinds: [{ id: 'spider.follows', description: '...' }]` here.\n- `block-types/writ-phase.ts` — reference for reading writs via `stacks.readBook<WritDoc>('clerk', 'writs')`. Same pattern for reading blocker phases during gate evaluation.\n- `spider.test.ts` — existing test rig. Uses in-memory fabricator and clerk; gate tests will extend this pattern.\n- `oculus-routes.ts` — Spider's own Oculus route contributions (`/api/spider/config`, session transcript/stream). Unrelated to this commission but confirms the existing route-contribution mechanism.\n\n### Clerk (`packages/plugins/clerk/src/`)\n\n- `types.ts` — `WritDoc.status?: Record<string, unknown>`, `WritPhase` union, `WritLinkDoc { sourceId, targetId, label, kind }`, `KindEntry`, `LinkKindDoc`, `ClerkApi`, `ClerkKit { writTypes?, linkKinds? }`.\n- `clerk.ts`:\n  - `ClerkKit` interface (line ~59) — `linkKinds?: LinkKindDoc[]` contribution field.\n  - `registerKitLinkKinds` (line ~217) — validates id format (kebab-case suffix after dot), enforces plugin-id prefix match, dedupes. Hard-fails on malformed. `spider.follows` is prefix-matched to `spider`, suffix `follows` — both pass.\n  - `link()` (line ~401) — upserts `WritLinkDoc`. Validates `kind` against the kit registry. Composite id: `{sourceId}:{targetId}:{normalized-label}`.\n  - `listKinds()` (line ~496) — returns registered `LinkKindDoc[]`. Consumed by Oculus to populate the dropdown.\n  - `setWritStatus(writId, pluginId, value)` (line ~592) — atomic read-modify-write preserving sibling sub-slots. Single writer API for `status.<pluginId>`. This is the only supported path for Spider to record its provenance.\n  - Phase transition validation — `ALLOWED_FROM` governs which phases can go to which. `open → stuck` and `stuck → open` are both allowed; Spider's gating path relies on both.\n- `tools/writ-link.ts` — already accepts `kind?` param.\n- `tools/writ-link-kinds.ts` — tool returns `{ kinds: LinkKindDoc[] }` or raw array with `json: true`. Route: `GET /api/writ/link-kinds`. Consumed by Oculus.\n\n### Oculus writ page (`packages/plugins/clerk/pages/writs/index.html`)\n\n- Single-page HTML+JS. ~1291 lines. Self-contained module; vanilla JS against `fetch`.\n- Datalist at line ~130 — `<datalist id=\"link-labels\">` with preset labels (retries/supersedes/fixes/duplicates/blocks). Not affected by this commission; the dropdown is additive.\n- Add-link form at line ~504-509 — target-id input + label input + Link button. Needs a `kind` dropdown inserted alongside (ordering/placement is a cosmetic decision).\n- `doAddLink()` (line ~758) — POSTs to `/api/writ/link` with `{ sourceId, targetId, label }`. Needs to include `kind` (or omit when blank).\n- API helper (line ~158) — standard fetch wrapper. Error surfaces already support inline display.\n- Kinds fetcher — *new code*. Call `/api/writ/link-kinds` on page load; populate a `<select>` with `<option value=\"\">(no kind)</option>` + one option per registered kind.\n\n## Adjacent patterns\n\n- **Contributing load-bearing metadata from a kit.** `writTypes` (Clerk) and `blockTypes` / `rigTemplates` / `rigTemplateMappings` (Spider) are existing kit-contribution shapes. `linkKinds` (Clerk) is the same pattern, already implemented. Spider's addition is purely declarative.\n- **Reading writs from Spider.** `block-types/writ-phase.ts` reads via `stacks.readBook<WritDoc>('clerk', 'writs').get(id)`. Same pattern for reading blocker phases.\n- **Writing writ phase from Spider.** The existing engine-cascade path in the rigs-book CDC handler uses `clerk.updateWritPhase(writId, 'stuck', { resolution })`. Same path is used for gating stuck (plus an added `setWritStatus` call for provenance) and auto-unstick (`stuck → open`, plus a `setWritStatus` clearing the cause).\n- **Short-id formatting.** `ratchet/src/tools/click-tree.ts` line ~18 defines `shortId(id) = id.split('-').slice(0, 2).join('-')`. Same formatting is needed for the human-readable resolution text (e.g. `w-mo3depkw`). Either import or replicate — replication is trivial and avoids cross-plugin dep (see D2).\n- **Per-plugin status worked example.** `docs/architecture/apparatus/clerk.md` line ~452 shows the canonical example `setWritStatus(writ.id, 'spider', { stuckCause: 'engine-failed', ... })`. **Note:** the doc's example uses `engine-failed` as a stuckCause value — but the brief prescribes `status.spider` is *not* written on the engine-cascade path. Doc/code discrepancy flagged in observations.\n- **Oculus dropdown-from-API.** No existing precedent inside the writ page for a kit-registry-sourced dropdown; the datalist-from-static-array is the closest. The pattern will be novel in this file but trivially simple (fetch + map to `<option>`).\n\n## Existing context & click lineage\n\n- **Design subtree** — `c-mo2e88aw-f4d5684cf385` and children. All concluded. Questions settled here include composition (conjunctive), direction (outbound-on-dependent), cycle handling (per-evaluation during graph walk), recovery semantics (auto-unstick), provenance (`status.spider`), terminal-state treatment per state (completed/cancelled release, failed cascades, non-terminal holds).\n- **Name + description** — `c-mo2zim46-8a9e69f209f3`. Concluded with the final `spider.follows` name and the prescribed description text.\n- **Id-format adjustment** — `c-mo3465sf-d9187bc9322a`. Concluded with the dot-separator form (`spider.follows`, not `spider:follows`).\n- **Status-convention design** — `c-mo33duvq-7f774446c6c9`. Concluded: the `status: Record<string, unknown>` slot on writs; single-writer-per-sub-slot rule; `setWritStatus` transactional API. This commission is the first live writer.\n- **No-DB-migration confirmation** — `c-mo33e1vs`. Concluded: the status field is implicit in existing Stacks storage; no schema change needed.\n- **Parked: visibility gap** — `c-mo301yp9-c186db746a77`. `open` overloads \"gated / eligible / running.\" Explicitly out of scope. Do not treat as a decision. If inventory touches Oculus writ-page rendering, stop at the add-link form.\n- **Prior substrate commissions (both dispatched before this one)**:\n  - Link-substrate rename — introduced `kind`, `listKinds()`, dot-separator id convention.\n  - Status convention — introduced `WritDoc.status` and `ClerkApi.setWritStatus`.\n\nBoth are assumed landed and verified by this commission's brief. No coordination needed.\n\n## Tool/route mapping\n\nClerk's `writ-link-kinds` tool maps to `GET /api/writ/link-kinds` via the Instrumentarium's `toolNameToRoute` (first hyphen splits resource/action). The Oculus page calls this route directly; no new route or tool is needed.\n\n## Doc/code discrepancies\n\n- `docs/architecture/apparatus/clerk.md` line ~452 uses `engine-failed` as an example `stuckCause` value in the Spider sub-slot. The brief prescribes that Spider's engine-cascade path does **not** write into `status.spider`. The doc's example is illustrative of *shape* but slightly mismatched with the prescribed writer convention. Noted in observations; no change to the doc in this commission (not in scope).\n",
  "scope": [
    {
      "id": "S1",
      "description": "Register the `spider.follows` link-kind in the Spider plugin so operators and tools can attach precedence links between writs.",
      "rationale": "The brief declares a new load-bearing kind contributed by Spider via `supportKit.linkKinds`. Before any gating logic can run, the kind must be registered so Clerk accepts it and Oculus can list it.",
      "included": true
    },
    {
      "id": "S2",
      "description": "Gate Spider dispatch on outbound `spider.follows` blockers, with conjunctive composition, failed-blocker stuck cascade, cycle detection, auto-unstick on recovery, and provenance recorded in `status.spider`.",
      "rationale": "This is the core behavioral change in the brief: Spider reads outbound `spider.follows` links during crawl, holds dispatch while any blocker is non-terminal, sticks the dependent when a blocker fails, sticks cycle members when the graph walk detects a cycle, and auto-unsticks when causes resolve. Provenance in `status.spider` is the mechanism that separates Spider-authored stucks from others.",
      "included": true
    },
    {
      "id": "S3",
      "description": "Add a `kind` dropdown to the Oculus writ-page inline add-link form, sourced from `listKinds()`, with inline error handling when Clerk rejects the submission.",
      "rationale": "The brief completes the Oculus side of the 'both label and kind are first-class' story. CLI already supports `--kind`; Oculus currently only offers label. Dropdown is additive; no broader UX redesign.",
      "included": true
    }
  ],
  "decisions": [
    {
      "id": "D1",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "What is the shape of the `status.spider` sub-slot written by Spider for gated/stuck writs?",
      "context": "This commission is the first live writer of any `status.<pluginId>` sub-slot. The brief prescribes `stuckCause: 'failed-blocker' | 'cycle'` but leaves the rest of the shape to the implementer. Future consumers (an Oculus gate-state column, other apparatus reading blocker history, human debuggers) will read this slot, and changing the shape later costs a schema-coordination sweep across those readers.",
      "options": {
        "minimal": "Just `{ stuckCause: 'failed-blocker' | 'cycle' }` on stuck. Absence means not-Spider-authored. No other fields.",
        "enriched-on-stuck": "On stuck: `{ stuckCause, blockerIds: string[], observedAt: string }` (cycle members listed in blockerIds for the cycle case). Absence still means not-Spider-authored. Nothing written while gated-but-not-stuck.",
        "enriched-always": "Write the slot whenever Spider has an opinion: while gated (`{ gated: true, blockerIds, observedAt }`), while stuck (`{ stuckCause, blockerIds, observedAt }`), clear when released/auto-unstuck. Enables a live gate-state column without Oculus re-walking the graph."
      },
      "recommendation": "enriched-on-stuck",
      "rationale": "Matches razor criterion 4 (shape of persisted inter-component data, Reach Test passes: future Oculus column + human debugging readers). Patch Test fails: once readers exist, changing the shape forces coordinated migration. The enriched-on-stuck shape gives future readers the structured detail the brief already implies ('the structured detail — which blockers, which phases, when observed — lives in status.spider') without paying the cost of writing on every poll. The `enriched-always` option writes churn on every crawl tick and conflates Spider's 'I have an opinion' with 'the writ is in a bad state.' Surfacing for patron because this is the decision that will be most visible in code once Oculus adds a gate-state column."
    },
    {
      "id": "D2",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "How is the short-id form produced for human-readable resolution text?",
      "context": "The brief prescribes resolution text like `Blocked by failed dependency: w-abc123` using the short-id form. Ratchet already has a `shortId` utility (`click-tree.ts` line ~18) that does `id.split('-').slice(0, 2).join('-')`. Spider does not currently depend on Ratchet.",
      "options": {
        "replicate": "Inline a tiny `shortId` helper in Spider. Three lines, trivial.",
        "import-from-ratchet": "Add a Spider→Ratchet dep and import the helper.",
        "hoist-to-shared": "Extract `shortId` into nexus-core or a shared utility package and import from both."
      },
      "recommendation": "replicate",
      "rationale": "Auto-decided. Not a razor match (no reach beyond Spider; not a vocabulary choice, not human-facing in a read-once-write-many sense). Three defaults apply: extend locally rather than routing through a cross-plugin dep. Replicating a 3-line utility is cheaper than introducing a plugin boundary. Hoisting would be premature for a single shared call site."
    },
    {
      "id": "D3",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "What algorithm detects cycles during gate evaluation?",
      "context": "The brief prescribes cycle detection happens per-evaluation during the graph walk (not a separate periodic scan). Classic options for directed-graph cycle detection on the fly: iterative DFS with a visiting/visited set, or union-find with edge additions. The graphs here are small (commission-level follows), so any correct algorithm works.",
      "options": {
        "dfs-visiting-set": "Standard iterative DFS per candidate writ with `visiting` (in-stack) and `visited` (fully-explored) sets. Any back-edge indicates a cycle. Report cycle members as the path from back-edge target to current node.",
        "per-walk-visited-only": "Track only a visited set per walk. If the same node is visited twice in one walk, it's a cycle. Simpler but doesn't distinguish diamond from cycle.",
        "whole-graph-precompute": "On each crawl, precompute the entire spider.follows graph and find all SCCs up front. Then gate eligibility lookups are O(1)."
      },
      "recommendation": "dfs-visiting-set",
      "rationale": "Auto-decided. Not a razor match (internal implementation detail of Spider's gate logic; no external consumer of the algorithm choice). Three defaults: use the correct, idiomatic algorithm. DFS with visiting/visited correctly distinguishes cycles from diamonds (which are legal) and gives a precise cycle-member set for the resolution text. The whole-graph precompute optimization isn't justified until profiling shows the walk is hot."
    },
    {
      "id": "D4",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "Does the gate introduce a new `CrawlResult` variant, or reuse the existing `blocked` variant?",
      "context": "`types.ts` defines `CrawlResult` as a discriminated union with variants including `blocked`. Today `blocked` is emitted by the rig-level block-type system (not `spider.follows`). The gate evaluation could emit the same `blocked` tag or a new tag.",
      "options": {
        "reuse-blocked": "Emit `{ kind: 'blocked', reason, writId, blockerIds }` using the same discriminator. Risks conflating two different block sources in telemetry.",
        "new-gated": "Add a `{ kind: 'gated', writId, blockerIds }` variant alongside `blocked`. Separates rig-level blocks from dispatch gating."
      },
      "recommendation": "new-gated",
      "rationale": "Auto-decided. Not a razor match by the Reach Test (variant is read only by Spider's crawl caller, emitted only by Spider). Patch Test passes: reversal is a trivial rename/merge. Three defaults: prefer failing loud on distinction — the two cases have different meanings (one is 'this writ's rig is blocked by block-types,' the other is 'this writ won't dispatch because its precedence graph isn't ready'). A distinct variant makes logs and tests self-explanatory."
    },
    {
      "id": "D5",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "How does Spider find stuck writs that may be eligible for auto-unstick?",
      "context": "On each crawl, Spider must re-examine writs currently in `stuck` phase whose cause is `status.spider.stuckCause` (its own writes). There is no existing `stacks` index on status sub-slot. Options are an in-memory list scan of all stuck writs, or a narrower query.",
      "options": {
        "scan-all-stuck": "Read all stuck writs, filter in memory to those with `status.spider?.stuckCause`, then evaluate each.",
        "maintain-in-memory-set": "Spider maintains an in-memory Set of its stuck writs, updated when it writes/clears. Risk: state drift across restarts (must rebuild by scanning on startup).",
        "add-stacks-index": "Introduce a new stacks index on `status.<pluginId>.stuckCause`. Much larger change across apparatus."
      },
      "recommendation": "scan-all-stuck",
      "rationale": "Auto-decided. Not a razor match (internal; no cross-component reader). Three defaults: prefer the simplest correct implementation. Stuck-writ counts are bounded (the operator notices them). In-memory set (option b) adds state-synchronization hazards for a micro-optimization. Adding a stacks index is scope-expanding for a feature that's poll-bounded by nature. If profiling shows the scan is hot, a follow-up commission can add the index."
    },
    {
      "id": "D6",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "What ordering of the crawl loop does gate evaluation slot into?",
      "context": "The crawl loop priority is `collect > processGrafts > checkBlocked > run > spawn`. Gate evaluation fits naturally inside `trySpawn` (before `spawnRig`) and inside a new auto-unstick pass. The question: is auto-unstick its own priority slot, or piggy-backed on `trySpawn`?",
      "options": {
        "inline-in-spawn": "`trySpawn` iterates open writs for dispatch AND also iterates stuck-with-spider-cause writs for auto-unstick. One pass through relevant writs, two possible outcomes.",
        "separate-phase": "Add a new `autoUnstick` phase before `trySpawn` that only handles stuck writs, then `trySpawn` only handles open writs. Cleaner separation of concerns.",
        "dedicated-priority": "Add a new top-level priority (e.g. between `checkBlocked` and `run`) named `reevaluateGates`. Explicit in the crawl log."
      },
      "recommendation": "separate-phase",
      "rationale": "Auto-decided. Not a razor match (internal to Spider; no external consumer cares about the crawl phase boundary). Three defaults: extend cleanly at the right layer. A separate `autoUnstick` phase keeps `trySpawn` focused on new dispatches and makes the two transitions (`open→stuck` and `stuck→open`) visibly distinct in the code. Inlining them muddles the control flow; dedicated-priority over-elevates an internal pass."
    },
    {
      "id": "D7",
      "scope": [
        "S3"
      ],
      "question": "Where does the `kind` dropdown sit relative to the existing label input on the add-link form?",
      "context": "The form currently has target + label + Link button. Ordering affects how operators read left-to-right.",
      "options": {
        "kind-then-label": "[target] [kind▼] [label] [Link]",
        "label-then-kind": "[target] [label] [kind▼] [Link]",
        "kind-before-everything": "[kind▼] [target] [label] [Link]"
      },
      "recommendation": "kind-then-label",
      "rationale": "Auto-decided under Patch Test — cosmetic. Kind is more load-bearing than label, so placing it adjacent to the target (which it qualifies) reads most naturally. Reversible in a few lines if the patron prefers otherwise."
    },
    {
      "id": "D8",
      "scope": [
        "S3"
      ],
      "question": "What is the label of the empty option in the kind dropdown (representing a kind-less link)?",
      "context": "A link with no kind is legal (`kind = null`, documentary). The dropdown needs a default option that the operator picks for that case.",
      "options": {
        "no-kind": "`(no kind)`",
        "label-only": "`— label only —`",
        "none": "`None`"
      },
      "recommendation": "no-kind",
      "rationale": "Auto-decided under Patch Test — cosmetic. `(no kind)` is explicit about what's being chosen and matches the existing parenthetical convention in the codebase's null-value affordances. Patron can rename trivially."
    },
    {
      "id": "D9",
      "scope": [
        "S3"
      ],
      "question": "When does the Oculus page fetch the list of kinds?",
      "context": "`listKinds()` via `/api/writ/link-kinds` returns a small list and rarely changes at runtime. The form needs the list populated before an operator opens it.",
      "options": {
        "on-page-load": "Fetch once at page init. Dropdown is ready when the form is opened.",
        "on-form-open": "Fetch when the operator first clicks into the add-link form. Marginally lazier.",
        "per-submission": "Re-fetch before every submission to catch registry changes. Overkill."
      },
      "recommendation": "on-page-load",
      "rationale": "Auto-decided. Not a razor match (no reach beyond the page). Three defaults: simplest correct behavior. Registry is small and stable; on-page-load costs one GET and keeps the interactive path zero-latency."
    },
    {
      "id": "D10",
      "scope": [
        "S1"
      ],
      "question": "What exact description text is registered for `spider.follows`?",
      "context": "The brief prescribes the description verbatim: *\"The source writ is a precedence-successor of the target: source cannot be dispatched until the target reaches a terminal state. Consumers define their own policy for what happens on each terminal state.\"*",
      "options": {
        "brief-verbatim": "Use the brief's prescribed text exactly."
      },
      "recommendation": "brief-verbatim",
      "rationale": "Pre-empted by the brief. The text is explicitly prescribed as verbatim. Recorded for completeness.",
      "selected": "brief-verbatim"
    },
    {
      "id": "D11",
      "scope": [
        "S1"
      ],
      "question": "What is the kind id — `spider.follows` (dot) or `spider:follows` (colon)?",
      "context": "Click `c-mo3465sf-d9187bc9322a` concluded the dot-separator form is the chosen id convention.",
      "options": {
        "dot": "`spider.follows`",
        "colon": "`spider:follows`"
      },
      "recommendation": "dot",
      "rationale": "Pre-empted by concluded click `c-mo3465sf-d9187bc9322a`. Clerk's validator also expects the dot form after the prior rename commission.",
      "selected": "dot"
    },
    {
      "id": "D12",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "What composition rule applies when a writ has multiple outbound `spider.follows` links?",
      "context": "The brief explicitly prescribes conjunctive — all blockers must release.",
      "options": {
        "conjunctive": "All blockers must release.",
        "disjunctive": "Any released blocker releases the gate."
      },
      "recommendation": "conjunctive",
      "rationale": "Pre-empted by the brief. 'Composition: conjunctive' under Non-negotiable decisions.",
      "selected": "conjunctive"
    },
    {
      "id": "D13",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "Which direction does Spider read — outbound on the dependent, or inbound on the blocker?",
      "context": "Same edges either way; the brief prescribes reading outbound on the dependent.",
      "options": {
        "outbound-on-dependent": "Read candidate writ's outbound `spider.follows` links; inspect target phases.",
        "inbound-on-blocker": "Read blocker writ's inbound `spider.follows` links."
      },
      "recommendation": "outbound-on-dependent",
      "rationale": "Pre-empted by the brief. 'Direction: outbound from the dependent' under Non-negotiable decisions.",
      "selected": "outbound-on-dependent"
    },
    {
      "id": "D14",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "Does Spider transitively cascade stuck (stick writs dependent on the newly-stuck one) in one pass, or let the next poll discover them?",
      "context": "The brief prescribes single-edge-per-poll cascade.",
      "options": {
        "single-edge-per-poll": "Spider sticks only the direct dependent; next poll handles transitive.",
        "atomic-transitive": "Spider walks and sticks all transitive dependents in one pass."
      },
      "recommendation": "single-edge-per-poll",
      "rationale": "Pre-empted by the brief. 'Stuck cascade scope: direct dependents only.'",
      "selected": "single-edge-per-poll"
    },
    {
      "id": "D15",
      "scope": [
        "S2"
      ],
      "question": "Does auto-unstick happen, or must a failed-blocker stuck be manually unstuck?",
      "context": "The brief prescribes auto-unstick when causes resolve.",
      "options": {
        "auto-unstick": "Spider auto-unsticks on the next poll when all causes are resolved.",
        "manual-only": "Operator must manually unstick even after causes resolve."
      },
      "recommendation": "auto-unstick",
      "rationale": "Pre-empted by the brief. 'Auto-unstick on recovery' under Non-negotiable decisions.",
      "selected": "auto-unstick"
    },
    {
