  "observations": "# Observations\n\n## Future follow-ups implied by this commission\n\n### Oculus gate-state column (parked concern)\nThe brief parks the open-phase visibility gap at `c-mo301yp9`, and the natural remedy is an Oculus writ-table column that reads from `status.spider`. This commission establishes the sub-slot shape that future work depends on (decision D1). When that follow-up commission lands, the `status.spider` reader will be a second-party reader of the same shape we're about to write for the first time — exactly the blast radius considered under razor criterion 4. If the patron anticipates needing more than `stuckCause` for the column (e.g., a \"gated\" indicator without stucking), revisit D1 now rather than after Oculus has wired up readers.\n\n### Stale resolution on auto-unstick\nWhen Spider auto-unsticks a writ (`stuck → open`, clearing `status.spider.stuckCause`), the writ's `resolution` field still contains the old human text (\"Blocked by failed dependency: w-abc123\"). `resolution` is not currently a per-phase field — it's written on terminal-like transitions but never cleared. After auto-unstick, the writ is `open` but carries a stale resolution naming the (now-successful) former blocker. Two reasonable stances:\n\n- **Acceptable historical breadcrumb.** `resolution` is read as \"most recent stuck reason,\" and a released writ carrying one is just lineage.\n- **Bug.** A writ in `open` with a \"Blocked by...\" resolution is semantically wrong; the auto-unstick path should clear or update it.\n\nNot in scope for this commission (the brief does not prescribe behavior either way), but worth patron awareness. A minimal fix would be: on auto-unstick, overwrite `resolution` with something like \"Auto-unstuck; blockers resolved.\" A follow-up commission could also reframe `resolution` as a phase-change audit trail rather than a single field.\n\n### Two distinct Spider→stuck paths with distinct conventions\nThis commission adds a second Spider→stuck transition path (gating) that writes `status.spider.stuckCause`. The existing engine-cascade path (rigs-book CDC → writ stuck) does *not* write the sub-slot by design. That asymmetry is load-bearing (auto-unstick uses absence as a signal) but not necessarily obvious to a reader of the code. Consider a brief comment on the engine-cascade CDC handler explaining why it stays silent on `status.spider`. Observation, not implementation request — the brief already makes the decision explicit.\n\nLonger-term, as more plugins write into `status.<pluginId>`, the engine-cascade path may deserve its own provenance marker (e.g. `status.spider.stuckCause = 'engine-failed'` to make the asymmetry purely a \"Spider owns all its stuck writes\" rule rather than \"Spider writes some stucks and not others\"). The doc example in `clerk.md` line ~452 already implies this future shape (see doc/code discrepancy below).\n\n## Doc/code discrepancies\n\n### `clerk.md` sub-slot example vs. brief prescription\n`docs/architecture/apparatus/clerk.md` line ~452 shows a worked example of `setWritStatus(writ.id, 'spider', { stuckCause: 'engine-failed', ... })`. The brief prescribes that the engine-cascade path does *not* write the sub-slot in this commission. The doc example is illustrating *shape*, not writer convention, but a future reader could easily take it as prescriptive. A one-line clarification in the doc (\"this is an example of *what Spider could write*, not what it currently does\") would prevent confusion. Not in scope for this commission — the brief does not ask for doc changes.\n\n## Performance / scaling notes (not bugs)\n\n### No index on `status.<pluginId>` sub-slot\nDecision D5 auto-decides in favor of `scan-all-stuck` for auto-unstick because stuck-writ counts are bounded by operator attention (stuck writs are noticed and resolved). If the guild grows to a regime where hundreds of writs are simultaneously stuck with Spider-authored causes, the scan becomes wasteful on every poll. A follow-up commission could add a stacks index on `status.<pluginId>.stuckCause`. Not needed today.\n\n### Per-candidate DFS vs whole-graph precompute\nDecision D3 auto-decides in favor of per-candidate DFS because the graph is expected to be small. If rig-graph density grows (many writs with many outbound `spider.follows` each), the per-candidate walk does redundant work across candidates on the same poll. Whole-graph SCC precompute on each crawl tick would amortize this, at the cost of more upfront work per poll. Not needed today.\n\n## Code-quality opportunities noticed in passing\n\n### Naming collision: `checkBlocked` vs gating as \"blocked\"\nSpider's existing crawl priority includes a `checkBlocked` phase that is unrelated to `spider.follows` gating — it checks rig-level block-types (writ-phase etc.). The brief speaks of \"blocked\" dispatch for the gate. Decision D4 resolves this by introducing a distinct `gated` `CrawlResult` variant, but the underlying naming remains: two different concepts of \"blocked\" coexist in the code. Possible follow-up: rename `checkBlocked` to `checkRigBlockers` (or similar) to disambiguate. Not in scope.\n\n### `spider.ts` size\n`spider.ts` is 2,262 lines, which already feels like it's carrying multiple responsibilities (main loop, CDC handlers, rig lifecycle, block-type registry). Adding gate-evaluation code will extend it further. A future refactor could split by responsibility — `crawl-loop.ts`, `cdc-handlers.ts`, `gate.ts`, etc. Mentioning for the punch list; not recommended as part of this commission.\n\n### Oculus writ page size\n`packages/plugins/clerk/pages/writs/index.html` is a 1,291-line single file mixing HTML, CSS, and JS. Adding the kind dropdown is additive and low-risk, but the file is pushing the maintainable limit for a vanilla-JS SPA. No refactor recommended here; this commission should be careful to follow the existing conventions even if they are cramped.\n\n## Substrate-consumer observations\n\n### First writer vs. \"first-party precedent\"\nThis commission is the first live writer of *any* `status.<pluginId>` sub-slot. That means whatever shape Spider chooses (D1) becomes the *de facto* convention the next consumer looks at as precedent. If the enriched-on-stuck shape is adopted, subsequent plugins will likely mirror it (field order, field names, timestamp format). This is a light form of vocabulary-setting that the razor's reach test covers for D1 — but worth keeping in mind when the patron reviews D1.\n\n### Clerk tool `writ-link-kinds` has a `json: true` flag\nClerk's `writ-link-kinds` tool already supports a `json: true` mode returning the raw array, vs the default human-readable table. The Oculus page needs the raw shape. This is not a behavioral concern — the `GET /api/writ/link-kinds` route returns structured JSON regardless of the tool's display mode — but worth noting that the existing tool is already API-friendly for programmatic consumers.\n"
}

/**
 * The Clerk — writ lifecycle management apparatus.
 *
 * The Clerk manages the lifecycle of writs: lightweight work orders that flow
 * through a fixed status machine (new → open → completed/failed/cancelled,
 * with stuck as a non-terminal "needs attention" state off open).
 * Each writ has a type, a title, a body, and optional codex and resolution
 * fields.
 *
 * Writ types are validated against the guild config's writTypes field plus the
 * built-in type ('mandate'). An unknown type is rejected at post time.
 * Kits may also contribute writ types via their writTypes field.
 *
 * See: docs/architecture/apparatus/clerk.md
 */

